                    <li><strong>5.7.8</strong> &mdash; <?php _e('Test coverage (slice 85 &mdash; pin TC_Fuzzy_Search_Service at ~100%). Third slice of batch 11 &mdash; the final 0% batch in the 100% coverage push. New tests/GTFuzzySearchServiceTest.php (15 tests / 43 assertions) pins includes/services/class-tc-fuzzy-search-service.php (17 statements) from 0% -&gt; ~100% line + method coverage. TC_Fuzzy_Search_Service is the stateless static-method helper that powers the per-table enable_fuzzy_search setting (#192). When the setting is on, the AJAX entry query expands each whitespace-separated word in the search term to also match via MySQL SOUNDEX so common typos and phonetically-similar strings surface results (Smth matches Smith, colour matches color, Jon matches John or Joan). The LIKE substring clause is always present so exact matches stay fast and correct; SOUNDEX is appended as an OR so it only widens the result set, never narrows it. Two public static methods, both exercised. is_enabled() covered &mdash; absent enable_fuzzy_search key returns false (existing tables keep exact-match behaviour); falsy values (false, 0, empty string, the literal zero string, null) return false via the not-empty check; truthy values (true, 1, the literal one string, yes string) return true. build_meta_where(wpdb, search_term, meta_alias=em_search) covered &mdash; return-shape contract (array with sql string key plus params list key); LIKE branch always emitted with the supplied meta-table alias as a meta_value LIKE param; esc_like wildcard escaping verified by feeding a payload containing both percent and underscore metacharacters and asserting the produced LIKE wildcard escapes them inside the wrapping percent-percent frame so a user-supplied percent cannot break out; custom meta_alias propagates into both the LIKE selector and every SOUNDEX selector, with the default em_search literal absent from the output. SOUNDEX OR-branch covered &mdash; single-word term emits exactly one SOUNDEX(meta_value) = SOUNDEX(param) clause with the bound parameter matching the input word; three-word phrase (John Paul Jones) emits three SOUNDEX clauses in declaration order with the LIKE parameter first followed by John, Paul, Jones (4 params total); the mb_strlen less-than-2 guard skips single-character ASCII tokens (a Smith b yields only Smith); empty search term produces only the LIKE clause (params is one entry of two percent signs, no SOUNDEX, no OR separator) because preg_split plus array_filter strip the lone empty token; whitespace-only term likewise emits no SOUNDEX. Trim semantics on tokens pinned &mdash; array_map trim strips leading/trailing whitespace from each split fragment before the length check so a term with embedded tabs and surrounding spaces yields the trimmed tokens as bound SOUNDEX params while the LIKE param preserves the original untrimmed term. Unicode whitespace handling pinned &mdash; preg_split with the unicode flag treats U+00A0 NO-BREAK SPACE as whitespace so a term joined by NBSP splits into two SOUNDEX clauses rather than being treated as one long word. Multibyte glyph guard pinned &mdash; a single CJK character measures as length 1 under mb_strlen and is skipped from the SOUNDEX expansion so the LIKE-only fast path holds for short unicode queries. Strategy notes: production type-hints wpdb, so the same in-file guarded placeholder class pattern from GTWritebackServiceTest (slice 76) and GTExceptionsTest (slice 27) is reused &mdash; class wpdb declared once under a class_exists wpdb false-guard, then a local TC_Test_Fuzzy_WPDB subclass provides the only dependency the production code touches (esc_like) and records every call so the bound LIKE parameter can be asserted. No wpdb mock collision with sibling tests because each test instantiates a fresh stub in setUp. No WP_Mock userFunction, no process isolation, no hook registration, no globals beyond the in-file stub. Patterns reused: slice 76 (GTWritebackServiceTest &mdash; wpdb