                    <li><strong>5.7.6</strong> &mdash; <?php _e('Test coverage (slice 83 &mdash; pin TC_Excel_Float_Service at ~100%; OPENS batch 11). First slice of batch 11 &mdash; the final 0% batch in the 100% coverage push. New tests/GTExcelFloatServiceTest.php (24 tests / 70 assertions) pins includes/services/class-tc-excel-float-service.php (26 statements) from 0% -&gt; ~100% line + method coverage. TC_Excel_Float_Service is the static-only presenter over PhpSpreadsheet that fixes #169 &mdash; float and decimal cell values were being routed through Sheet::fromArray(), which casts every value to a PHP string and causes two downstream bugs in Excel: numeric strings like 3.14 are stored with cell type String instead of Numeric so referencing formulas error, and ambiguous strings like 1.5 or 12.30 are mis-identified as dates and re-rendered as 1-May / Dec-30. The service interposes an is_numeric_value() decimal-regex gate between the export pipeline and the cell writer so numeric values are written with explicit DataType::TYPE_NUMERIC and a FORMAT_NUMBER_COMMA_SEPARATED1 number format that pins decimal precision and prevents Excel date auto-formatting. Three public static methods, all exercised against a real PhpOffice PhpSpreadsheet Spreadsheet instance (autoloaded via composer rather than mocked, so DataType + NumberFormat side effects are observable through the actual object graph &mdash; the suite breaks if the PhpSpreadsheet API drifts). is_numeric_value() covered &mdash; int / float fast-path returns true for positive, zero, and negative scalars; non-string / non-int / non-float fallthrough returns false for null, true, false, empty array, array containing a numeric string, stdClass instance; empty-string guard returns false (Excel renders blank cells, not zeros); decimal-regex accepts unsigned (3.14, 1000.00, 0.5), signed (-0.75, +12.30, -1000.00), integer-looking strings (42, -17, +1 &mdash; the optional decimal group makes these legal), whitespace-trimmed inputs (3.14 with surrounding spaces, tab and newline around -5); decimal-regex rejects alphabetic (abc), currency ($3.14), percent (3.14%), comma-separator (3,14), scientific notation (1e5, 2.5E-3), date-like (2025-09-24, 1.2.3, 12/30), bare decimal-point edge cases (single dot, .5 with leading dot, 5. with trailing dot &mdash; the regex requires digits on both sides when a decimal is present). set_typed_value(Worksheet, coord, value) covered &mdash; numeric branch writes TYPE_NUMERIC for 3.14 float, 42 integer, and the 1.5 decimal-string with the FORMAT_NUMBER_COMMA_SEPARATED1 format code applied to getStyle(coord) getNumberFormat() (verified by reading back getFormatCode() and asserting equality with the constant); string branch writes TYPE_STRING for the Hello World literal and leaves the format code at the default FORMAT_GENERAL (the else branch must not touch number format); empty-string writes through TYPE_STRING with value empty; null, true, false flow through string-cast in the else branch without fatal (null -&gt; empty, true -&gt; 1, false -&gt; empty). write_data_row(Worksheet, values, row) covered &mdash; empty array (foreach skips, no fatal, row untouched); single value at row 1 lands at A1 with the numeric type round-tripped; mixed row [1.5, text, 7] progresses across A1, B1, C1 with each cell receiving the correct typed write; row anchor honoured (passing row 5 writes to A5, B5 and leaves A1..B4 null); wide row past column Z (27 sequential values land at A2, ..., Z2, AA2 &mdash; confirms Coordinate::stringFromColumnIndex is being called with a 1-based incrementing counter, not the raw foreach key); associative-key input (name=&gt;Alice, score=&gt;95.5) writes to A3 and B3 in declaration order, confirming the internal col counter is used rather than the array keys. Strategy notes: PhpSpreadsheet is autoloaded via vendor/phpoffice/phpspreadsheet, so the test instantiates a real Spreadsheet + active sheet rather than mocking the Worksheet class. This 